column168: On May 1, 2023, at 1650 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar personnel in Williamsburg, Kentucky regarding the release of approximately 2 gallons of Acrylic Resin Solution (Resin solution, UN1866, 3, III) from (1) 55-gallon metal drum.  The release was reportedly due to a puncture to the drum and was contained to a 5’ x 1’ area of the trailer floor.  No drains or waterways were affected by the release.  Contractors were dispatched to clean up the release using absorbents, hand tools and the proper PPE.  All waste debris generated was containerized in (1) 55-gallon metal drum.  The waste drum was then transported offsite by contractors for proper disposal.

Package located at our ramp location in Koln Germany came in contact with a forklift during sort operations.  This contact caused a shipment containing drums of UN1760 to become damaged and begin to leak its contents.  it is estimated 12 L was able to escape the drum before the local fire brigade was called in to handle the spill.  As per local regulations, when the spill was contained the fire brigade took custody of the shipment and released the site back to the employees

column168: On May 2, 2023, at 1230 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar personnel in Deer Park, Texas regarding the release of approximately 1 quart of Biotrol 12.5 (Hypochlorite solutions, UN1791, 8, III) from (1) 275-gallon plastic tote.  The release was reportedly due to a loose cap and was contained to a 6’ x 6’ area of the trailer floor.  No drains or waterways were affected by the release.  Contractors were dispatched to clean up the release using absorbents and the proper PPE.  The cap on the tote was tightened and forwarded on to the consignee.  All waste debris generated was containerized in (1) 55-gallon poly drum.  The waste drums were then transported offsite by contractors for proper disposal.

Hepaco  was  dispatched  to  the  site.  Upon  the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed  that the released material impacted a  10ft-by-4ft area of the trailer floor and a 2ft-by-2ft area of the concrete dock floor and estimated that two (2) gallons of material was released due to load shift during transit. Hepaco personnel removed all the cargo from the trailer and confirmed that only two (2) 1-gallon plastic jugs were crushed and approximately twelve (12) boxes were  impacted  by  the  released  material.  Hepaco  personnel  neutralized  the  impacted  areas  and deployed granular absorbents to the impacted areas and collected the spent absorbents and placed them into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum and placed  an impacted pallet, cardboard, and debris into an additional 55-gallon poly drum and both drums were staged onsite at the terminal prior to the contractor demobilizing.  The  nondamaged  cargo  was  shipped  on  to  the  consignee.  The  generated  waste  will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

column168: On 5/3/2023 at approximately 0945, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 4472417, reporting an undeclared dangerous goods shipment, which consisted of one fiberboard box, filled with several COVID-19 tests that appear to be used.  The shipment was discovered open druing unloading due in part to the use of masking tape, which is an improper closure.  Although there was no release of DG,  the shipment was not prepared in accordance with IATA Regulations, having shipped without markings, labeling, packaging.  The shipment is bieng held, pending an FAA investigation.

column62: Conveyer or Material Handling Equipment Mishap
column168: SequenceEvent: QA was notified of Hazardous spill on loadside. PPE was applied and package was inspected. Spillage was contained and package was pulled from sortation and placed in bag lined tote with cleanup and brought to hazcage for further inspection. No injuries resulting from this spillage. Due to nature of damage it is believed that a package fell from the sortation belt onto the hazmat, causing the internal damage. DescribePack: Large dent on lower side of internal container, created break that allowed leaking of contents. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Spillage was contained and package was pulled from sortation and placed in bag lined tote with cleanup and brought to hazcage for further inspection. No injuries resulting from this spillage.

SequenceEvent: Package was found by incompatible conveyance items getting ready to be placed on main conveyor belt. Exterior packaging was found to be wet and starting to fray. Package was brought to the Quality Assurance area for inspection. Upon inspection, no inner packaging materials used to buffer the 4 plastic jugs of Isopropanol. The jugs had loose caps, causing the product to leak and soil the labels on the jugs. DescribePack: The four jugs of Isopropanol leaked due to loose caps, causing the box to become wet and fray along the edges of the exterior packaging. The labels on the individual bottles of Isopropanol became soiled by leaked product. DurationRel: 36 and MitigateEffect: When package was found, gloves were used for PPE to protect from corrosive materials. Package was likely sitting in a trailer over the weekend, thus unable to be tended to sooner.  Tracking system shows package had been in St Paul station 4/29/23, then the trailer with the package was unloaded at Fargo station 5/1/23.

column168: On May 3rd, 2023 at 1931 personnel in the CSXT Howell Yard discovered NATX38424, a loaded tank car of Acetone leaking from the protective housing. The car was isolated the shipper was notified (CHEMTREC Report #2023-05-03-00321). Marion environmental Inc., a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a steady drip coming from the protective housing, upon further inspection it was determined the liquid line valve was not in the closed position and the secondary securement plug had no thread sealant allowing product to pass through the valve. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative- Ara Rainey, ara.rainey@sabic.com, 812-833-1558. Contractor personnel closed the valve, applied thread tape to, and properly secured, the secondary closure plug. and applied thread tape to the secondary securement plug.

On May 5, 2023, at 0551 ET, XPO Logistics terminal LTU suffered a cargo related release of UN3266 “Principal” to the trailer floor and asphalt lot below. . ERTS dispatched ERS of OK to investigate, secure and remediate the release. On May 5, 2023, at 0846 ET, ERS personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 8-gallons of product released to a 5' x 10' area of the trailer floor and a 10' x 20' area of the asphalt lot under the trailer due to a forklift puncture. Oil Dri was deployed, and citric acid utilized to neutralize the impacted areas. The damaged drum was placed into a 95-gallon poly overpack and the cleanup debris was containerized into (2) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

On May 03, 2023, Frontier Tank Lines contacted ERTS to report that Unit #206072 was involved in a rollover accident that released diesel fuel near Exit #26 I-40 in Sayre, OK. The exact quantity of diesel was unknown at that time, but the caller stated that an estimated fifty yards of the surface had been impacted. The driver was no longer on the scene, but the local fire department was on site. No drains or waterways were reported to have been impacted. On May 03, 2023, ERS of OK was dispatched to the site with a vac truck.  Trooper Bussy, informed ERTS that there was a 15 ft-by-15 ft area of soil impacted with diesel that was about 10 in deep. Before the contractor arrived with the vac truck, the local fire department’s hazmat team was on site and would manage the tanker and truck being uprighted. At 0600 ERS arrived onsite to begin evaluating the release. At 0700 ET, ERS utilized their vac truck to evacuate the standing pool, which was at capacity with 2800 gallons onboard, a second vac truck was called for to remove all standing liquid. While waiting for the second vac truck the crew placed an absorbent boom down to secure the area for future excavation. At 1200 ET, the second vac truck arrived so the crew continued to collect the material.  At 1400 ET, ERS updated the site assessment of the impacted soil area being 300ft of a ditch and from 10ft to 1ft back and forth.  The main area that was impacted measured 200ft long and was estimated 15 -30ft wide.  At 1500 ET, ERS completed all ER clean-up on May 4, 2023. The scene was staged with a poly tarp, and multiple booms below the impacted soil. The area was flagged and is currently secure until further remediation is scheduled to recover the impacted soil.

column168: During normal switching operation a train crew observed liquid running down the side of the car and originating from the area of the manway.  The car was set out and the area was isolated.  I response contractor was called to investigate and repair the leaking car.  The contractor found the single bolt on the clincher style manway was less than tool tight.  The manway was opened and the gasket was inspected but no defects were noted.  The manway was resecured in a tool tight condition.  The contractor also inspected the other fittings and no exceptions were found.  The exterior of the car was neutralized and cleaned.  No product reached the ground.

column42: LITHIUM ION BATTERIES PACKED WITH EQUIPMENT
column168: May 4th, 2023. 7 of 8 pieces arrived on flight 175/04MAY. 1 piece was broken open and lithium-ion batteries fell out from the shipment. The RSA working on the inbound freight from the flight brought it to my attention and did further research. The batteries were not declared in this shipment, but nature of goods stated to be tools and clothes. This shipment originated in BOI and was screened TSA K9. I opened the box the rest of the way and did a physical search and discovered 3 - 20v lithium-ion batteries not attached to equipment. Did a physical search on the boxes that contained tools due to finding undeclared lithium-ion batteries. There were tools that the batteries could have attached to but were in two separate boxes.
column169: When a customer states that the nature of goods of their shipment is tools, that needs to have further clarification. Tools is one of the trigger terms and could potentially have dangerous goods such as lithium-ion batteries. Asking questions such as, does the tools need batteries to power them? If so, what type of batteries and how many?

On May 4, 2023, at 1652 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar personnel in Carlstadt, New Jersey regarding the release of approximately 50 gallons of Phosphoric Acid 85% (Phosphoric acid, solution, UN1805, 8, III) from (9) 275-gallon plastic totes.  The release was reportedly due to a a number of factors, including loose bungs and punctures during transit.  No drains or waterways were affected by the release.  Contractors were dispatched to clean up the release using absorbents and the proper PPE.   Waste generated for this response included (8) empty 55-gallon poly drums previously containing released product, (9) empty 275-gallon plastic totes, (12) 275-gallon plastic totes of phosphoric acid product, (3) 55-gallon poly drums containing phosphoric acid impacted PPE, Oil Dri and soda ash, and (1) 55-gallon poly drum of phosphoric acid impacted rinse water.  All waste was then taken offsite by contractors for proper disposal.

column168: On May 3, 2023, at 1954 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar personnel in Mentmore, New Mexico regarding the release of approximately 1 gallon of DELTA-THERM™ AR 8501 Polyol (Chemical under pressure, n.o.s., UN3500, 2.2) from (1) 3500-gallon metal tank.  The release was reportedly due to a loading strap striking the release valve.  No drains or waterways were affected by the release.  Contractors were dispatched to clean up the release using a pressure washer and the proper PPE.  The released material impacted rinse water was containerized in (1) 55-gallon metal drum which was then taken offsite by contractors for proper disposal.

On May 5, 2023, at 1435 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar personnel in Troutdale, Oregon regarding the release of approximately 1 cup of VEX244-506C Vinyl Ester Resin (Resin solution, UN1866, 3, III) from (1) 55-gallon drum.  The release was reportedly due to a forklift puncture.  No drains or waterways were affected by the release.  Contractors were dispatched to clean up the release using absorbents and the proper PPE. SequenceEvent: Trailer was being unloaded and two walls in, hazmat package was discovered, crushed and leaking. QA was called immediately, and package handlers vacated the trailer. DescribePack: Half the box was crushed, thereby popping the lids off two of the four gallons and squeezing most of the liquid out of them. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Absorbent sheets were used to cover the wet flooring of the trailer and the hazmat was placed in its lined, red bin. Both the hazmat and the affected packages were removed.

column168: Patriot Environmental Services was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 15ft- by-8ft  area  of  the  asphalt  parking  lot  and  a  20ft-by-8ft  area  of  the  trailer  floor  and  estimated  that approximately fifty (50) gallons of material was released from a 330-gallon poly tote due to improper preparation for transit. Patriot Environmental Services personnel stated that ESTES terminal personnel had  deployed  granular  absorbents  to  the  impacted  asphalt  prior  to  the  contractor’s  arrival.  Patriot Environmental Services personnel deployed additional granular absorbents to the impacted trailer and gathered all spent absorbents and placed them into six (6) 55-gallon poly totes. The remaining product from the poly tote was transferred to five (5) 55-gallon poly drums. All waste was staged onsite at the terminal  prior  to  the  contractor  demobilizing.  The generated  waste  will  remain onsite for the ESTES terminal team to coordinate disposal.

The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On May 4, 2023, four (4) one-gallon pails of paint (UN1263) were damaged by a load shift and released approximately one (1) gallon to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Environmental Remediation Consultants (ERC) to remediate the impacted surfaces. ERC personnel restacked the non-damaged pails for continued shipping, then deployed degreaser and absorbents to the release. The crew then utilized hand tools to collect and containerize the four (4) damaged pails and all paint impacted material in one (1) 55-gallon drum for disposal.

ERTS will dispatched a contractor to drop off a 55-gallon poly drum. Once it arrived, XPO placed the waste into the drum which was then staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

A HAZMAT SHIPPMENT WAS VISIBLY DICSCOVERED BY AN UNLOADER IN SECTION C, WET IN APPEARANCE, AND EMITTING A STRONG SOUR ODOR. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PACKAGE HE EVACUATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR. DMP WAS CONTACTED AND WITHIN TWO MINUTES A DESIGNATED RESPONDER ARRIVED DONNING THE PROPER PPE. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE AND APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED (NO SPILLAGE OUTSIDE OF CARTON), THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAP ON 1 OF 4 PLATIC 1 GALLON JUGS WAS LOOSE BY ONE FULL ROTATION, CAUSING APPROXIMATELY 9 OUNCES OF THE LIQUID TO LEAK THROUGH THE BREACH AND INTO THE CARTON. THE INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL CONSISTED OF A CORRUGATED DIVDER AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A DOUBLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX RATED AT A 51 LBS/IN EDGE CRUSH TEST (ECT).

RESPONDER RECEIVED A CALL FOR A LEAKING HAZMAT. RESPONDER DONNED FULL PPE AND BROUGHT SPILL CART AND DECISION TREE. UPON INSPECTION, RESPONDER FOUND IT WAS A FLAMMABLE LIQUID HAZMAT AND THE BOX WAS DAMP. RESPONDER FOLLOWED THE RESPONSE SHEET FOR A FLAMMABLE LIQUID AND CONTAINERIZED THE SPILL, THEN BROUGHT IT BACK TO DMP FOR PROCESSING.

FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS VISUALLY DISCOVERED STAINED IN APPEARANCE BY AN UNLOADER. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG SHE EVACUATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HER IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR. DMP WAS CONTACTED AND WITHIN LESS THAN 1 MINUTE A DESIGNATED RESPONDER ARRIVED, DONNING THE PROPER PPE. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED (NO SPILLAGE OUTSIDE OF CARTON), THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAP ON 1 OF 1 PLASTIC 1-GALLON JUG WAS LOOSE BY 1/2 ROTATION CAUSING APPROX. 8 OUNCES OF THE LIQUID TO LEAK THROUGH THE BREACH AND INTO THE CARTON. THE INETRNAL THERE WAS NO INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A SINGLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT 200 LBS PER SQ INCH BURSTING TEST.

column168: On May 2, 2022, an unknown amount of 5-gallon pails of paint were damaged during transit and released approximately ten (10) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from EnviroCare, Inc. (ECI) to remediate the site. ECI personnel utilized granular absorbents and hand tools to collect and containerize all paint impacted material into four (4) 55-gallon drums for disposal by R+L.

column168: On May 2, 2023, one (1) 275-gallon tote of sulfuric acid (UN2796) and one (1) 275-gallon tote of sodium hydroxide (UN1824) were punctured by a forklift and released approximately one (1) gallon of product total to the dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from EnviroServe (ES) to remediate the impacted site. ES personnel transferred the sulfuric acid into one (1) new 275-gallon tote. The crew then replaced the lid on the 275-gallon tote of sodium hydroxide. ES utilized absorbent wipes to wipe down the impacted totes, then containerized all impacted absorbent wipes in two (2) 55-gallon drums for disposal by R+L.

column168: A courier domiciled at our station location in Minneapolis, MN. Picked up a package from a body sculpting clinic and over the course of their route started to hear a rattling from the package.  They also stated when they went to look at the package they felt the contents shift and saw that it was being shipped to an oxygen company.  Looking for documentation as to the contents, they found Class 2.2 labels placed in the document pouch behind the shipping airbill.  The courier presented the package to the dangerous goods specialist when they arrived at the station and with a manager present, the package was opened to find a cylinder marked as containing compressed helium.  There were no marking placed on the outer package itself to indicate the contents inside.  Package has been secured pending FAA investigation.

A fiberboard box was discovered leaking during sort operations at the SW2A facility. The fiberboard box contained four glass bottles containing Chloroform. One of the bottles had broken open releasing it's contents. The package was placed into a steel salvage package. A new declaration will be obtained for movement back to the shipper.

column168: ABF employee was trying to remove freight with forklift and 3 boxes fell. Spilling contents onto trailer floor and edge of trailer.

A forklift operator was loading 2 pallets, of UN1133 into trailer 88996 at dock door 85. A forklift arm punctured one box, which contained 2 metal buckets that the OS on site advised were roughly 5 gallons each. The liquid that dripped out of the side of the trailer dripped onto blacktop. The OS advised that they would place everything in a recovery drum after letting the powder do its job. The OS did not feel they needed a spill crew called out, I advised that if that changed to call me back.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal LSL experienced a UN2831 Methyl Chloroform release from a 55-gallon metal drum due to a forklift puncture impacting their dock floor. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup.  Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed terminal personnel applied Oil Dri to the impacted area. Approximately 20-gallons of product released to a 20' x 30' area of the dock floor due to a forklift puncture. Additional absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted area. The damaged drum containing approximately 35-gallons of product was placed into a 95-gallon poly over pack. The impacted absorbents and cleanup debris were placed into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: During the quality control inspection process for arriving drums to Veolia's 10-day intransit facility in Port Allen, LA, a small puddle of unknown liquid (approximately ½ cup) was observed at the edge of a pallet. After informing the supervisor on duty, the pallet was pulled aside and inspected. One drum of waste was found with a pinhole leak ~3 inches from the edge of the bottom of the drum. The leak appeared to not be from stress or gradual wear, and it's believed that the drum may have been compromised during the generator's loading process or a manufacturing fault in the packaging exists since this is the second time an incident like this has occurred with this generator. The drum was overpacked into a salvage drum, and the spill was cleaned using oil dry.
column169: Veolia will inform the shipper to review/improve their handling procedures as well investigate the possibility of faults in the packaging being used.

column168: While offloading containers at Veolia's 10 day intransit facility in Dayton, OH a Veolia employee noticed the container he was unloading had a slow leak from the bottom. Veolia employees set the drum down and placed spill pads around the bottom while we further investigated the material and condition of the container.  The investigation showed that the container had a significant leak when we tried to move it to its side or lift it for over packing. The container leak slowed down when we placed the drum flat on its bottom. We decided to try to overpack the container by placing it on its side and quickly sliding an 85 gallon over pack over the bottom of the drum. Ideally the overpack would catch most of the material that leaked out of the drum while we attempted the overpacking process. Unfortunately the drum totally failed as we placed it on its side allowing most of the material inside to flow into the trailer. Spill dry and spill pads were already placed in the area so the spill was contained at the time of release. The initial spill was a few gallons but once the bottom split/cracked an additional 35 gallons was released. The spilled material was cleaned up using floor dry/cat litter and the area was decontaminated. All spill clean up material was properly cleaned up by the Veolia team and we confirmed that no material released outside of the trailer.
column169: Veolia's investigation showed that this particular container was refurbished and it was actually manufactured in 2018. It was also identified that the container was stored outside while it was at the drum refurbishing company. Veolia believes the age of the drum and the former storage conditions may have led to the splitting or cracking at the bottom of the drum. The Veolia team has been asked to inspect any container they accept from a drum refurbishing site. By inspecting the drums before providing them to customers or use them ourselves we may be able to identify an issue and remove the drum from service before an incident occurs.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal LOO experienced a UN3082 Gunslinger P+D release from a 275-gallon poly tote due to a forklift puncture. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted areas. The material was transferred from the damaged tote into a new one. The damaged tote was then cut up and containerized along with all cleanup debris into (4) 55-gallon metal drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

The Heavyweight area of our ramp location in Williston VT received a pallet with it's contents wrapped in black opaque shrink wrap.  When package was about to be loaded to be delivered, an employee noticed the shrink wrap was ripped in a corner and a drum under the shrink wrap was marked and labeled as a class 9 Environmentally Hazardous UN 2077.  Inspection of the contents found several drums all marked and labeled for travel as a regulated dangerous good, however, dangerous goods paperwork was not offered with this pack nor were the labels duplicated on the outer most package.  it is possible package originated in Germany and was offered to FedEx via DHL Supply chain, however, this can not be substantiated.  Package has been held at station pending FAA investigation.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: On May 11, 2023, one (1) 55-gallon drum containing Nugen NR Disinfectant Wipe Concentrate (UN160) was punctured by a skid steer and released approximately one-half gallon (0.5) of product to the dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted surface. FCE personnel overpacked the damaged 55-gallon drum into one (1) 85-gallon overpack. The crew then deployed granular absorbents and utilized hand tools to containerize all Nugen NR Disinfectant Wipe Concentrate impacted material in one (1) 55-gallon drum for disposal.

column168: Customer requires a sample from the discharge pipe of trailer before offloading. Driver removed 2 inch cap on discharge pipe and opened the internal valve to flood pipe between the external valve.  Driver did not realize the external valve was open prior to departing our facility, so when he attempted to fill the tube he immediately put product on the ground due to head pressure and open internal and external valves. He shut the internal valve immediately and driver contacted his supervisor for assistance. An external emergency response contractor was hired to clean up the customer's site.    Response cost is an estimate at this time.

column168: Driver arrived at Part B Storage facility to unload, opened his trailer, and started unloading the drums.  It was found that multiple drums had shifted In the trailer and 4-6 drums fell partially over off on the pallets.  There were 32 drums of p# 97-8905 picked up from Azz Galvanizing on s/o#13600996 shipping on manifest#024447890JJK. We removed 3 drums from the trailer and picked up the partially fallen drums and that's when it was found some of the drums were leaking out of the top of the open-head poly drums.  There was material on the floor of the trailer, totaling <5-gallons.  While inspecting more drums it was found more drums showed evidence of slight leaking out of the top of the drums.  All employees left the trailer and ER Contractor was called for cleanup.    It was found that the drums were closed with latch rings instead of bolt rings and were improperly closed per closure instructions (zip tie not fully tight and not within control holes).  Breaking event during transportation caused drums to be compressed and forced a small amount of the waste liquids out the top and coated the side of the drums.  Additionally, the pallets were in poor condition causing some of them to break during transportation.
column169: Enforce customer to follow closure instruction per supplier for drum tops.  Inspect pallets for good condition before accepting for transportation.  Review driver safety and operation procedures for waste pickups.

column168: On 5/08/2023, the BNSF Los Angeles hub reported Unit RNLU 100597 (Waybill Hazardous) (Sodium Hydroxide UN3266) leaking a substance from the rear of the container that did reach the ground. In the interest of safety the unit was moved to the containment area. On the behalf of the shipper, BNSF approved contractor United Pumping was contacted and dispatched to complete inspection and any necessary remediation.  Interior inspection revealed palletized cases varying in size and IBC Totes 2 rows wide, the pallets were stacked multiple layers high throughout the container, Source of the leak was determined to be one IBC Tote containing Sodium Hydroxide mixture . The cause for the Leak was determined to be previous damage to the IBC Tote contributing to the material leak. Total quantity of leaked liquid was approximately 30 gallons of product.  Impacted materials and surfaces were cleaned and neutralized. The damaged IBC Tote and soiled material was removed and will be disposed of by contractor in coordination with the Shipper (R&L Carriers).  Disposal is pending.

column168: On May 30, 2023, at 1429 hours, FRA Hazmat inspector Kevin Cash reported GATX 37155, a loaded tank car of Creosote located in the CSX Montgomery Yard, was leaking from the manway. The car was isolated and the shipper, Blackwater Midstream, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2023-05-30-00318). Marion Environmental Inc. (MEI), a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found two of the six manway cover bolts were less than tool tight and the manway cover gasket was significantly worn. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative- Blake Chatagnier (504-414-2040, bchatagnier@bwcterminals.com). Contractor personnel replaced the manway cover gasket, properly secured all manway cover bolts, and wiped away residual product that was adhering to the outside of the car. Upon completion the car released for transport.

column42: NITRIC ACID OTHER THAN RED FUMING, WITH MORE THAN 70 PERCENT NITRIC ACID
column168: On May 11, 2023, three (3) 5-gallon pails of nitric acid were damaged due to a load shift and released approximately fifteen (15) gallons of product to the trailer floor and asphalt. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from GrayMar Environmental Services (GES) to remediate the site. GES personnel deployed neutralizing agent and granular absorbents to the impacted areas. The crew then utilized hand tools to collect all UN2031 impacted material into four (4) 55-gallon drums and three (3) drum liners for disposal.

column168: CTCX 733705 Styrene car was found leaking from the combination housing in the Galesburg Yard. CTCX 733705 was inspected by the Mechanical Hazmat Responder and it was determined the liquid valve 4 bolt flange bolts were less than tool tight. This allowed product to be released. Mechanical tightened the liquid valve four flange bolts to mitigate the release. A BNSF Contractor was dispatched to inspect the car after repairs were made by BNSF Mechanical.
column169: Ensure the Shipper's pre trip inspection process and securement procedures are properly followed before releasing a hazardous material package into shipment.(NAR:270)

column168: On 5/16/23, BNSF Portland IMF notified LARS of destination unit RDWY 140990 (billed LTL HAZ, UN 1760, Combustible Liquid) which was observed to be leaking a liquid substance during the de   ramping process. Upon inspection US Ecology observed a standard LTL shipment with multiple differentiating pieces of cargo unsecured at different heights. The unit was double stacked with very heavy cargo on top plastic palletized HAZ containers, while in transit the cargo shifted, allowing the plastic containers to be crushed causing the leak. All leaking containers leaked through the cap when squeezed, no holes where observed.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: On 05/21/23, the BNSF Los Angeles IMF reported YRCU 450262 (Waybill Hazardous) as dripping a clear   like substance upon deramp and was immediately moved to the containment area. On behalf of the shipper, United Pumping was contacted and dispatched to complete the inspection and any necessary remediation. Inspection of the containment area revealed approximately one (1) quart of product lost outside of the unit while Interior inspection revealed a mixed load of palletized cargo including a secondary load supported by load bars. A 36X36 airbag was used for lateral securement although was found deflated while doorway securement was provided by a load strap and bullboard. The source of the leak was determined to be originating from four (4) car   sized batteries found tipped on their sides releasing liquid. The source of the leak was determined as hazardous material UN 2794, contractor estimates the total loss to be under one (1) gallon before remediation took place. The cause of the leak was the result of failed packaging (stretch film) which was used in an attempt to unitize palletized batteries.
column169: Ensure loads are blocked and braced using BNSF Railway LARS guidelines.

column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS WITH NOT LESS THAN 20 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 40 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (STABILIZED AS NECESSARY)
column168: THE HAZMAT AUDITORS CALLED AND SAID THEY HAD A LEAKING HAZMAT. UPON ARRIVAL IT WAS AN OXIDIZER/CORROSIVE LABELED HAZMAT THAT WAS OXYGEN BLEACH. RESPONDER FOLLOWED THE OXIDIZER RESPONSE SHEET, PUT ON PPE AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL. RESPONDER TOOK IT BACK TO DMP FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. RESPONDER SOLIDIFIED ALL 1.5 GALLONS USING SODIUM BICARBONATE AS ITS PH WAS 2. RESPONDER BAGGED IT INTO GREEN BAGS AND BEGAN TO ENTER IT INTO ETT. RESPONDER FOLLOWED COC AND CONTACTED BASE AND ENVIORMENTAL COORDINATOR WHO CALLED AN OUTSIDE RESPONDER TO THE SCENE. ONCE THEY ARRIVED, THEY CLEANED IT UP AND PUT IT IN A 55-GAL PLASTIC DRUM.
HAZMAT RESPONDER RETREIVE PACKAGE AND TRANSPORTED TO DMP AREA.

column168: On May 17, 2023, one (1) 5-gallon pail of paint (UN1263) was damaged due to a load shift and released approximately one-half (0.5) gallon of product to the trailer floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from GrayMar Environmental Services (GES) to remediate the site. GES personnel overpacked the damaged pail into one (1) 55-gallon drum, then deployed absorbents and neutralizing agent to the released material. The crew then utilized hand tools to collect all paint and paint impacted material in the previously stated one (1) 55-gallon drum for disposal.

column168: On May 11, 2023, one (1) 275-gallon tote of UN3264 was punctured by a forklift and released approximately 150-gallons of product to the loading dock floor, pallets, and surrounding cargo. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from HazChem Environmental (HCE) to remediate the site. HCE personnel deployed a neutralizing agent and granular absorbents to the impacted area and worked them in with hand tools. The crew hand pumped the remaining product to one (1) new 325-gallon tote. Cres utilized a Sawzall to dismantle the damaged 275-gallon tote. All UN3264 impacted material was containerized into eight (8) 55-gallon drums for disposal.

column168: Our driver had just stopped at the Longstreet Inn hotel for the night, when he was conducting his post-trip inspection of the vehicle he observed a liquid leak on the ground near the front of the trailer. He entered the trailer and was able to locate a drum that had split and was leaking near the bottom of the drum. He was able to stop the leak by ensuring the bungs were tight and tipping the drum on its side and applying a patch until the response crew was able to place the drum into a salvage drum (overpack).

column168: First Call Environmental was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 1ft-by-1ft area of the trailer floor and estimated that six (6) gallons of material was released from fifteen (15) 1-gallon plastic  jugs  due  to  the  freight  shifting  during  transit.  First  Call  Environmental  personnel  deployed granular absorbents to the impacted area and then swept up the  spent material. The damaged  jugs and  spent  absorbents  were  placed  into  one  (1)  55-gallon  poly  drum  and  was  staged  onsite  at  the terminal prior to the contractor demobilizing. The undamaged product was sent on to the consignee. The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

column168: Truck and loaded tank trailer in route to Pryor Ok. When truck pulled into the Oklahoma weigh station, it was observed that there was a drip coming from the internal valve area on the tanker. The weigh station moved the tanker to a containment area. It was later determined that a faulty internal gasket caused the leak. The fire department responded to contain the leak. An emergency response and remediation crew were dispatched to the scene in order to transfer of the load into another tank trailer and perform the necessary clean up and remediation of the site. The load was successfully transferred into another tanker and transported to destination. The cleanup and remediation of the site have been completed.

The shipper loaded tank car (TC) overnight, 5/15/23 and was shipping it out today to a private storage facility. This TC car was offered into transportation on 5/16/23. During a regular HM inspection, the TC was discovered leaking auto refrigeration, observed on B end liquid eduction valve. The FRA HM Inspector did not open bonnet cover but accessed the valve through the opening in the wall pf protective housing. He safely climbed down the left side ladder to make his notifications.  The HM is described as 1 Tank Car, 152,250 pounds of UN 3220, Pentafluoroethane, Class: 2.2. The TC was in a train just outside the shipper's gate, the railroad was switching out plant. The rail crew put leaking TC back into shipper's facility for repair. The shipper will re-weigh the TC to determine if any measurable quantity was lost.
column169: Customer will use instrumentation to check for leaks moving forward on all outbound loads.

column168: This drum was crushed due to a shift in the load. The root cause of this incident is improper load securement. When the load shifted it caused this drum to become crushed and the denting of the drum caused a breach in the side wall of the drum near the bottom allowing all of the contents of the drum to be released.
column169: The branch responsible for loading this trailer was coached on proper load securement. The use of load securement straps, dunnage and blocking and bracing were discussed and reiterated to this team. Had this load been properly secured, this drum would not have sustained damage while in-transit and this incident and release could have been avoided.

column168: Truck and Van trailer with waste load of metal drums was in route from UT to NY. Driver had stopped at a service plaza in West Unity OH for a rest break. Driver performed a walk around and noticed a drip coming out of the trailer. The local authorities were notified. The Police and Fire Department responded to the scene. The Fire Department placed a containment pool under the drip coming from the trailer. An emergency response crew were also dispatched to the scene to determine the cause of the leak and perform the clean up and remediation. It was determined that 6 drums were leaking inside the trailer. The drums were placed in overpacks. The load was transported on to destination. The small amount of product that reached the ground was cleaned up and disposed of properly.

On 05/12/2023, at 1535 hours, personnel in the CSXT Aliquippa Yard discovered PPRX 55120, a loaded tank car of Pentanes, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the Shipper, National Response Center, and Pennsylvania Department of Environmental Protection were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2023-0512-00223). Specialized Professional Services, Inc, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the liquid valve primary flanged connection to the fittings plate was observed with 2 of 4 securement nuts less than tool tight. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Tim Nelson, phone 346.312.9881. Contractor personnel relieved all vapor pressure from the car, tightened all securement nuts. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.   Cause Code: 270 NARRI: 100

On 5/17/23, A Univar Solutions driver made a delivery to a customer. Upon being spotted, driver checked with the customer operator on the tank level and was told it was at 60% capacity and that the 2492 gal load would fit. Customer operator informed the driver that there were no site gauges but he would monitor the tank fill from the top. After 20 mins, the operator yelled out to the driver to shut off the pump. The customer operator informed the driver that he'd made an error and was distracted, which lead to the tank being overfilled. Material was contained within the containment area. Customer operator took ownership of the overflow error. Estimate 15 gallons of methanol spilled in containment. No injuries.  Spill was cleaned up. Note: Failure code selected was most representative of the incident.

On 5/02/2023, at 0308, personnel on the CSXT Main Line Columbus subdivision at mile post CD46.2 discovered VTGX 17533, a loaded tank car of Phosphoric Acid Solution, leaking from the Bottom Outlet Valve (BOV). The car was isolated and the shipper, Brenntag Global Marketing, National Response Center (NRC) incident #1366153, and local Fire and Police departments were notified (CHEMTREC Report #2023050200021). James Courtney, CSX Manager of Hazardous Materials, and EnviroServe and Arcadis, both CSXT emergency response contractors, were dispatched to the scene and found VTGX 17533 actively leaking. The issue was identified as a defective BOV valve with an unsecure secondary closure and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper (D.E. Duke 484-793-5119). Contractor personnel installed a new 2-inch plug in the BOV secondary closure cap after discovering the original plug was unserviceable and remediation efforts of the impacted area began immediately. The leak was secured and the car was moved to the CSXT Marion Yard for offloading, tank cleaning, and prep for Home Shop.  Upon onloading it was discovered that the BOV operating handle was properly actuating the BOV; causing the valve to remain open while the BOV operating handle was in the closed position.

column42: DANGEROUS GOODS IN MACHINERY OR DANGEROUS GOODS IN APPARATUS
column168: SequenceEvent: Lawn mower with gas and oil still in the machine was shipped improperly. Pkg was transported in a manner that allowed it to leak due to no orientation arrows. Too much weight for the pkg caused the carton to rip as well. DescribePack: Gasoline leaked from the fuel cap and oil leaked from the crankcase through the carburetor wetting and contaminating the contents and carton. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Pkg with contents sideways was placed on a rolling cart and staged by an open dock door until authorized and properly trained personnel could investigate, inspect and report the incident.

column168: SequenceEvent: A used gasoline powered lawn mower was being returned with gasoline in its tank. A strong smell of gasoline prompted personnel to remove the pkg from system flow. Pkg was sent to QA where it was later taken to the Hazmat Processing Area for inspection and reporting. DescribePack: Spilled gasoline was found outside the fuel tank as well as several ounces of gasoline still in the fuel tank which leaked due to a loose gas cap. Released liquid appears to have been contained to the contents of and the inner packaging. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Pkg was placed upright on an open cart as there is no way to secure it in a salvage drum/container.

column168: Crews reported a strong odor near TILX 190640. There was also an old lid gasket that was compressed and covered in product.  The two worn gaskets were removed, and a temporary Teflon gasket was installed.  The lid was resecured, and the release was stopped.
